Oh, yes. Manned spaceflight does have an element that is like art -
although more in the spiritual realm than the aesthetic.

But it also relates to practical necessity.

If we *did* have magic FTL spaceships, that could be churned out in
quantity, the way Detroit makes cars, then space would serve as a
direct outlet for population pressure.

The Basques or the Armenians or the Tibetans or the Parsees or the
Maronites or the Copts could fly off to find, in a distant galaxy, an
Earth-like planet of their very own, on which they could grow to be a
nation of a hundred million people, and preserve their language and
culture forever by establishing an economic infrastructure all their
own sufficient to support making their own Hollywood-quality movies in
their own language, and writing software for an operating system
designed for their language, and so on and so forth.

