If I could interject a serious comment into your clusterf**k:

The main purpose of the space program was national prestige;
specifically, a demonstration of the relative power of American rocket
and missile technology, relative to those of our potential adversaries
and competitors.

It was a cultural sublimation of the militarization of space.  Back in
the 1950's, the Air Force had the lead in America's nascent space
efforts.  But their interest was largely military, of course.  Giving
the new NASA agency the lead in space put a more humanistic face on
America's space efforts.

IIRC, back in 1960, rocket thrust and the alleged "missile gap" were
actually discussed in the Kennedy-Nixon presidential debates.  It hasn't
been an issue of national concern like that lately.  These days, we tend
to measure national prestige by other yardsticks, especially economic
productivity, and advances in computers and electronics.

